Prologue
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The King of Frost looked down at his wife from his throne, his royal advisor standing beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He frowned at the thought.
The little girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The King of Frost thought a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into the wild. It's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell was not always a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the North, the non-magical kingdom. In the South, a kingdom full of fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn themselves apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
Le Sud était acculé, et sa famille royale aurait fait n'importe pour stopper le bain de sang. Ils proposèrent que leur unique princesse devienne la reine du Nord et porte un fils destiné à être le futur roi. Ensuite, le Sud se serait allié au Nord pour former un même royaume. Le Nord avait accepté, et la princesse Eirwen avait épousé le prince Akull.
"Je vous en supplie, mon altesse, en échange de la vie de mon enfant, faites ce que vous voulez de moi, enfermez-moi, bannissez-moi ou même, tuez-moi", plaida la reine Eirwen, en tenant fort son enfant dans ses bras.
Le roi de Glace baissa le regard sur sa femme, du dégoût dans les yeux. Peut-être, peut-être aurait-il pitié d'elle. Celle avec qui il vivait depuis vingt-deux ans, qui avait toujours pris soin de lui, dans ses heures les plus sombres, qui avait donné naissance à ses fils.
"Soit, l'enfant pourra vivre au palais", commença-t-il, arrachant un soupir de soulagement à sa femme. "Cependant", ajouta-t-il, "vous serez exécutée".
Le conseiller et la reine Eirwen elle-même partagèrent un regard horrifié. Elle baissa doucement le regard. "Oui Altesse", dit-elle en s'inclinant.
The King of Frost ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's empty chambers. Once that was done, he ordered the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the villagers could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the villagers cried out in outrage at seeing their only queen, the kindest, about to be killed. Some wept, others screamed and tried to attack the guards, while others questioned what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made her entrance. The user of fire. The former queen Eirwen was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruellest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire set the gallows on fire, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
"Survive, Kari". That was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the most distant room on the left side of the always-frozen palace's southern wing. The attendants passing by always wondered what was inside that room, terrified of what could be found within. The rumors of the servants danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late wife of the King of Frost, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be freed.
"They couldn't be more mistaken," thought Ivory as she walked toward the southern wing, while the attendants went back and forth whispering to each other. They have no idea what is in that room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to iel, because iel was the only person allowed to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"; murmured Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but after all, where else could she have been?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory, remembering the time when iel had entered without asking for permission.
A knock echoed from inside. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though iel had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to the standards of normal people, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was colder than anywhere else in the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have been trapped inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook are you reading?" asked Ivory, sitting next to Kari on her bed.
